        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our pointing is centered on the A2204 BCG nucleus. 
The CO(1-0) line for A2204 (z=0.1521) is redshifted to 100.05 GHz in B3.  
At this frequency the ALMA field of view is about 1 arcminute, corresponding to about 160 kpc, which largely covers the entire region of interest for our study. 

Our sensitivity estimate is based on previous single-dish IRAM 30m observations of A2204, compared with real ALMA Cycle 0 observations of a cluster of similar CO(1-0) line brightness and located at a similar redshift (A1664, z=0.128).

The CO(1-0) line peak measured by IRAM is 1.5 mK, and the line width is about 250 km/s (see Table 5 of Edge 2001).  
We note that this IRAM peak emission is very similar to that of A1664 (1.7 mK), a cool core cluster that has recenly been successfully detected and imaged in CO(1-0) by ALMA in Cycle 0 (Russell et al. 2013).  In particular, the published map of A1664 show that a high fraction (&gt;50%) of the integrated CO flux is concentrated in the central ~3 kpc.  

By analogy with this real ALMA observation of a cluster similar to our target, we conservatively assume that 50% of the peak emission is concentrated in the central 3 kpc.  At z=0.1521 this radius corresponds to an angular diameter of about 1.2 arcsec, which is our desired angular resolution.

The estimated peak brightness in the central ALMA beam of 1.2 arcsec is therefore 
1.5 mK * 0.5 * (beam_IRAM=24" / beam_ALMA=1.2")^2= 300 mK.  

Given the line width of ~250 km/s, the lowest FDM spectral resolution of 976.563 MHz (2.926 km/s) is sufficient for our purposes. These spectral channels will be binned together to reach a 10 sigma detection in each 25 km/s channel. Indeed, in order to perform the kinematic study proposed, we need to sample the line in about 10 channes, therefore our sensitivity request is calculated by integrating over 25 km/s channel.
This yields a desired sensitivity of 30 mK, which corresponds to 0.354 mJy.  

We note that this sensitivity requirement represents an improvement by a factor ~1.5 with respect to the sensitivity level of current ALMA observations of cool core clusters (Russell et al. 2013, McNamara et al. 2013), therefore we are confident that our observations will detect the central CO emission, and likely also the fainter, more extended emission.
By comparison with the Halpha images (Jaffe et al. 2005, Oonk et al. 2011) we expect a maximum size of the CO emission of about 40 kpc ~ 15 arcsec, which is within the 12 m array maximum recoverable scale.

Continuum: 
For a proper continuum subtraction and calibration purposes we added 3 sidebands for the continuum.
The estimated global flux density was extrapolated from the available multi-frequency data available in literature (source: NED).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
